SIMPLE: notary
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Notary
<hw>No"ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Notaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>notaire</ets>, L.
<ets>notarius</ets> notary (in sense 1), fr. <ets>nota</ets> mark. See
5th <er>Note</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who records in shorthand what is said or done;
<as>as, the <ex>notary</ex> of an ecclesiastical body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eng. & Am. Law)</fld> <def>A public officer who
attests or certifies deeds and other writings, or copies of them,
usually under his official seal, to make them authentic, especially in
foreign countries. His duties chiefly relate to instruments used in
commercial transactions, such as protests of negotiable paper, ship's
papers in cases of loss, damage, etc. He is generally called a
<altname>notary public</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Notate</ent>⟦br⟧
